I originally thought, that it might work with list comprehensions, but I couldn&#39;t think of a way to do it. The problem just somehow intrigued me and I had to try it.

So you have a class:

	public class Consumer
	{
		public Consumer(Provider provider)
		{
			// ...
		}
	}

And this class has the following dependency:

	public class Provider : BaseProvider
	{
		public Provider()
			: base()
		{
			// ...
		}
	}

And this dependency has a base class:

	public class BaseProvider
	{
		public BaseProvider()
		{
			// ...
		}
	}

And now in the constructor of `BaseProvider` you want to know for which caller it is being initialized?

You can&#39;t.

The dependency injection framework will be initializing the `Provider` service _before_ instantiating the `Consumer` class. So you won&#39;t be able to obtain this information, especially not from the stack trace. 

This is an XY problem. If you need to know _who_ is calling a class, you&#39;re doing something wrong. What you _could_ be looking for, is a parameterized constructor in `Provider`, that gets called with different parameters depending on who needs it, in order to alter its behavior. But that&#39;s a different question altogether.

For the latter, see for example https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53884417/net-core-di-ways-of-passing-parameters-to-constructor.

