the idea is to :

1. pop() an item from the stack, whenever stack&#39;s peek() element is same as j-th element of second array, and increase j;
2. else, simply push i-th element from the first array into the stack
3. continue until value of i is less than the first array or value of j is less than the second array.
4. repeat step 1 for the rest of the elements for the second array.

Now check, if your stack is empty or not; if it is empty print: yes else print: no

Here is the java code for the same .. 

    public static void main(String[] args) {
		int [] a = {1, 2, 3};
		int [] b = {3, 1, 2};
		Stack&lt;Integer&gt; stack = new Stack&lt;Integer&gt;();
				
		int i = 0, j = 0;
		for(; ;) {
			if(i == a.length || j == b.length) break;
			/* pop element from stack, whenever a match found..(step 1) */
			if(!stack.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; stack.peek() == b[j]) {
				stack.pop();
				j += 1;
			}else {
                /* simply push the item for other case (step 2) */
				stack.push(a[i++]);
			}
		}
		while(j != b.length) {
            /* continue for rest of the elements of second array (step 4) */
			if(!stack.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; stack.peek() == b[j]) {
				stack.pop();
				j += 1;
			}else {
				break;
			}
		}
		
		System.out.println(stack.isEmpty() ? &quot;Yes&quot; : &quot;No&quot;);
	}

